<%= page_header "Reader Mode" do |h| %>
  <%= h.breadcrumb "Kitchen Sink", kitchen_sink_path %>
<% end %>

<%
  long_document = <<~MD
    # System Architecture Overview

    This document outlines the high-level architecture for the new event processing
    pipeline. It covers data flow, service boundaries, and deployment topology.

    ## Data Flow

    Events enter the system through a unified ingestion API. Each event is validated
    against a schema registry, enriched with metadata from the user service, and
    routed to the appropriate processing queue based on event type.

    The pipeline processes events in three stages:

    1. **Validation** — Schema validation, deduplication, and rate limiting
    2. **Enrichment** — User context, geo-IP, and feature flag resolution
    3. **Routing** — Fan-out to downstream consumers based on event type and tenant

    ### Validation Stage

    All incoming events are validated against versioned JSON schemas stored in the
    schema registry. Invalid events are routed to a dead-letter queue with detailed
    error metadata for debugging. The validator supports schema evolution — new fields
    can be added without breaking existing producers.

    Deduplication uses a sliding window of event IDs (default: 1 hour) backed by a
    distributed cache. This handles the common case of producer retries without
    requiring exactly-once semantics at the transport layer.

    ### Enrichment Stage

    The enrichment stage attaches contextual data to each event:

    - **User context**: Display name, team membership, permission level
    - **Geo-IP**: Country, region, timezone (using MaxMind GeoIP2)
    - **Feature flags**: Active experiments and feature gates for the user

    Enrichment is performed asynchronously using a scatter-gather pattern. Each
    enricher runs independently with a 100ms timeout — if any enricher fails, the
    event proceeds with partial enrichment rather than blocking the pipeline.

    ### Routing Stage

    Routing rules are defined declaratively in a YAML configuration file. Each rule
    specifies a predicate (event type, tenant, enrichment fields) and a list of
    destination topics. Events can be routed to multiple destinations simultaneously.

    ## Service Boundaries

    The system is decomposed into five services:

    | Service | Responsibility | SLO |
    |---------|---------------|-----|
    | Ingestion API | Accept and validate events | 99.99% availability, p99 < 50ms |
    | Schema Registry | Store and serve event schemas | 99.9% availability |
    | Enrichment Workers | Attach contextual data | p99 < 100ms per enricher |
    | Router | Fan-out events to consumers | 99.95% delivery within 5s |
    | Dead Letter Processor | Handle failed events | Best effort, manual review |

    ### Ingestion API

    The ingestion API is a stateless HTTP service deployed behind a load balancer.
    It accepts batched event payloads (up to 100 events per request), validates each
    event independently, and publishes valid events to the processing queue. Invalid
    events receive synchronous error responses with schema violation details.

    ### Schema Registry

    The schema registry provides a REST API for managing event schemas. Producers
    register new schema versions; the ingestion API fetches schemas at startup and
    caches them with a 60-second TTL. Schema compatibility checks prevent breaking
    changes (removed required fields, type changes) from being registered.

    ## Deployment Topology

    All services run on Kubernetes with horizontal pod autoscaling based on CPU and
    queue depth metrics. The ingestion API scales on request rate; enrichment workers
    scale on queue backlog. A circuit breaker pattern protects downstream services
    from cascading failures.

    ## Migration Plan

    The migration from the legacy monolith to this architecture will proceed in three
    phases over 8 weeks:

    1. **Phase 1** (weeks 1-2): Deploy ingestion API alongside legacy endpoint, shadow
       traffic for validation
    2. **Phase 2** (weeks 3-5): Migrate producers one team at a time, starting with
       lowest-volume event types
    3. **Phase 3** (weeks 6-8): Decommission legacy endpoint, enable advanced routing
       rules, onboard remaining consumers
  MD

  short_document = <<~MD
    # Quick Note

    This is a short document to demonstrate that reader mode works with brief content
    too. The overlay scales gracefully regardless of document length.

    - Point one
    - Point two
    - Point three
  MD
%>

<%= page do %>
  <div class="<%= card_classes %>">
    <%= card_header("Long Document", "A multi-section technical document — click the expand icon to open reader mode.") %>

    <div class="px-4 py-5 @sm:p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-4">
        <%= icon(:document_text, classes: "h-5 w-5 text-zinc-400 dark:text-zinc-500") %>
        <span class="text-base font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-100">System Architecture</span>
        <span class="text-sm text-zinc-500 dark:text-zinc-400">Draft</span>
        <%= reader_mode do %>
          <%= reader_mode_button(tooltip: "Reader mode") %>
          <%= reader_mode_dialog(title: "System Architecture") do %>
            <%= render_markdown(long_document, plan: true) %>
          <% end %>
        <% end %>
      </div>

      <%= render_markdown(long_document, plan: true) %>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="<%= card_classes %>">
    <%= card_header("Short Document", "Reader mode with minimal content.") %>

    <div class="px-4 py-5 @sm:p-6">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-4">
        <%= icon(:document_text, classes: "h-5 w-5 text-zinc-400 dark:text-zinc-500") %>
        <span class="text-base font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-100">Quick Note</span>
        <%= reader_mode do %>
          <%= reader_mode_button(tooltip: "Reader mode") %>
          <%= reader_mode_dialog(title: "Quick Note") do %>
            <%= render_markdown(short_document) %>
          <% end %>
        <% end %>
      </div>

      <%= render_markdown(short_document) %>
    </div>
  </div>
<% end %>
